<div class="xar-mod-body">
    <img src="#xarTplGetImage('admin_generic.gif', 'base')#" alt="official icon" width="96" height="96" class="xar-module-icon" />
    <h2><xar:mlstring>Overview</xar:mlstring></h2> <h3>
            <xar:mlstring>What is it?</xar:mlstring>
    </h3>
        <p>
            <xar:mlstring>The AuthLDAP module allows you to authenticate a user with an LDAP server.  The AuthLDAP module forwards the username and password from the login screen to the LDAP server for authentication.</xar:mlstring>
        </p>
    <h3>
        <xar:mlstring>How to use it?</xar:mlstring>
    </h3>
    <p>
        <xar:mlstring>From the menu, you have one choice.  "Modify Config".</xar:mlstring>
            <ul>
                <li><xar:mlstring>Modify Config -- From here, you can allow a user that has account information in LDAP to be automatically added to the Xaraya database and allowed to login. You can also setup the synchronization settings for LDAP groups.</xar:mlstring></li>
                <li><xar:mlstring>Manually Sync Groups -- This will resynchronize the imported LDAP groups. It may be long the first time if you have lots of Xaraya users imported from LDAP, or lots of (sub)groups to import.</xar:mlstring></li>
            </ul>
            <xar:mlstring>To synchronize the groups, we recommand to setup a job entry in the scheduler module. You need to call the function in (module:authldap, type:admin, function:syncgroups). The module has some caching mecanism for LDAP user profiles, so you can run this job frequently, for example every 30 minutes, without fearing about resource usage.</xar:mlstring>
    </p>
    <h3>
        <xar:mlstring>Included Blocks</xar:mlstring>
    </h3>
    <p>
        <xar:mlstring>There are no included blocks with the AuthLDAP Module</xar:mlstring>
    </p>
     <h3>
            <xar:mlstring>Included Hooks</xar:mlstring>
    </h3>
    <p>
        <xar:mlstring>There are no included Hooks with the AuthLDAP Module</xar:mlstring>
    </p>

